title: Mingus just keeps swimming
text: 10/13/2015 11:50:00 AM Mingus just keeps swimming Mingus Swimmer Sean Williams dives into the pool during a race earlier this year. Williams came in second place in both the 50 meter and 100 meter freestyle during their meet with Flagstaff. Williams was two 100thï¿½s of a second behind the winner in the 50 meter freestyle and in the 100 meter freestyle Williams was six tenths of a second behind the first place finisher.(Photo by Greg Macafee) Greg MacAfee Reporter COTTONWOOD - The state meet is about a month away for the Mingus Swimming and Dive team, and Marauders are accomplishing personal bests all over the pool. "It is exciting to work with such an awesome group of dedicated athletes and students," said Head Coach Gretchen Wesbrock.Over the past two weeks, the Mingus Swim and Dive competed in two different events, the first one taking place at the Brophy Swim and Dive Invitational. With over 80 divers competing in the Invitational, Mingus divers, Aspen Stanton, Autumn Stanton, Garrett Jobe and Brandon Gemmil competed in their first. "Although they did not advance into the 2nd round of competition, each had success in completing dives that had only learned weeks prior," Wesbrock said. "It was exciting to see all the hard work of Coach Kyle Lathom and the divers pay off in their first large meet of the season."On the swimming side for the Marauders, the boys finished 15th overall in the meet out of 26 teams, that were both Division I and Division II. Speedster Sean Williams beat his own Mingus High School record in the 100 meter freestyle with a time of 49.26, this placed him 4th overall at the Brophy Invitational. Williams also finished 9th in the 50 meter freestyle with a time of 22.57. Caleb Furey set his season best in the 100 meter breaststroke, finishing 9th overall with a time of 1:04.11. Josh Holcombe was one of many Marauders who set a new personal best, beating his previous time in the 100 meter freestyle by 10 seconds. The girls also had their highlights in the pool. The 200 medley relay team of Emily Dorris, Hannah Arwine, Rylie Burke, and Skylar Mohr swam a provisional qualifying time for state, finishing in 2:14.62. Dorris also swam for another provisional qualifying time for state in the 50 meter freestyle. She beat the provisional time by .05 seconds finishing at 27.45. She also set a personal best in the 100 meter backstroke with a time of 1:11.28. Danni Schulz set a new personal record in the 50 meter freestyle, beating her previous best by two seconds. Sarah Bramblett, Anissa Zorrilla, and Hannah Arwine all set new personal bests as well during the Brophy Invitational. Bramblett swam her personal best in the 100 meter freestyle with a time of 1:09.54. Zorrilla set her personal best in the 100 meter freestyle as well but came in two seconds faster than Bramblett, finishing in 1:07.86. Arwine set her personal best in the 100 meter backstroke beating her previous time by four seconds, finishing in 1:15.86. For the first time, Emily Grasso swam the 100 meter butterfly in a qualifying meet and set a personal best for herself finishing in 1:25.02. Christine Wills also set a season best in the 100 meter butterfly, clocking in at 1:28.17. After traveling to Brophy for the Invitational the Marauders had off until October 8th in which the Marauders hosted Flagstaff High School. In the meet the girls were able to take home a victory over the Eagles, 93-67. The boys had a little less success as they were defeated, 56-110. The overall combined score of the teams was, Flagstaff 177, Mingus 149. "This was a fantastic meet overall with fast swims from both MUHS and Flagstaff High School," Wesbrock said. Sean Williams had another successful meet but his two races might have left a little bit of a sour taste in his mouth. Williams again raced in the 50 meter and 100 meter freestyle. In both races he placed 2nd. In the 50 meter freestyle Williams finished two 100th's of a second behind the first place finisher. In the 100 meter freestyle, the speedy senior finished six tenths of a second behind the first place finisher. Williams wasn't the only swimmer coming in a close second place. Caleb Furey finished 2nd in the 100 meter breaststroke with a time of 1:06.74, the first place finisher clocked in at 1:06.45. Furey also racked up a first place finish in the 200 meter inter medley. The boys 200 yard freestyle relay also brought in a 1st place finish with Sean Williams, Fletch Fangman, Caleb Furey, and Dallin Gordon. In the girl's portion of the race, Skylar Mohr, Emily Dorris, and Rylie Burke all brought home first place finishes for the Marauders. Mohr finished 1st in the 200 meter freestyle and also placed 2nd in the 500 meter freestyle. Dorris finished 1st in the 100 meter backstroke while taking home 2nd in the 50 meter freestyle. Burke went home victorious in the 100 meter backstroke, and also took home 3rd place in the 50 meter freestyle. The girls also won the 400 yard freestyle with team members Christine Wills, Anissa Zorrilla, Emily Grasso, and Sarah Bramblett. As the Marauder head into fall break, they will head into Sedona on Thursday for the Mingus Cup with Sedona Red Rock and Northland Prep Academy. The Mingus Cup will be followed with an Invitational meet at the Mona Plummer Aquatic Center at Arizona State University on October 24.-- Follow Greg Macafee on Twitter @greg_macafee and Instagram @VerdeValleyNews
